Now, I don't know about this particular incident and maybe there is real evidence or admission of guilt.

But keep this in mind, if for whatever reason somebody decides they want to ruin you, so long as they know you and have potentially been along with you, they can claim they are your victim and it can then be virtually impossible to prove you didn‚Äôt do it. If they knew you 30 years ago, this is even more likely, because who can remember and gather enough evidence about what they were doing 30 years ago to mount a defense. 

We stopped needing hard evidence to convict people of sexual offenses, now just an unsupported accusation from one victim is enough to convict. I'm going to be honest. TYT are, in my opinion, too harsh, biased, and even too liberal for me, even though I like them. I don't watch their videos that often anymore, and I don't like how quickly they, in my opinion, often jump to politically-fueled conclusions.

However, I completely appreciated this segment. It was cathartic. His sarcastic, curt responses to admitted victim-blaming was great, and he seemed as disgusted and perplexed as I feel.

 Hannity is a despicable human. Normally I would not use such strong language for someone just because I disagree with them, but his treatment of this situation proves it. Not because acknowledging that some people make false accusations is bad, or because discussing reasons behind such false accusations is bad.

 He simply has no compassion, empathy, respect for women, or ability to look beyond his momentary political gain. He makes himself sound like an idiot, and his guests are vicious, selfish people whom I'd never want to have the misfortune of interacting with in real life. They seem to view women and even young girls in general as predatory temptresses who deserve punishment. It's sad, in a way, to see women sell out their own gender to appeal to the extreme fringes.

Tl;dr As a casual viewer of TYT who is fairly critical of all news sources, I really liked this video.

I don‚Äôt know how to feel about all these ‚Äúallegations‚Äù, I understand the law is written to protect women so they are comfortable coming forward and that trauma can have devastating effects on people it‚Äôs completely understandable that someone would remember an assault from 10, 20, 40+ years ago. What I don‚Äôt understand is why these traumatized and victimized women come forward to the public and media knowing that if you went through trauma you wouldn‚Äôt want to invite public scrutiny and opinion. Why do these men and women come forward to the media instead of the police or use the law? Furthermore why do we as a nation accept allegations as definitive proof of someone‚Äôs guilt, it‚Äôs almost as if the court of public opinion has replaced our actual legal system. I think women should have legal recourse to be able to pursue legal action against their abusers, but we cannot as a nation allow for the court of public opinion to determine someone‚Äôs guilt. 

We need to maintain innocence until proven guilty instead of this guilty until proven innocent mindset and in the law. False allegations are just as destructive as sexual abuse, and there is no legal recourse to resolve false allegations as no court will pursue legal penalties against a false accuser to ‚Äúprotect‚Äù other women‚Äôs perceptions of safety in coming forward.

It should be no surprise that women do not need any evidence to bring a case against someone they alleged assaulted or abused them and that is simply unacceptable.

If someone will have a criminal and civil case brought against them there must be some definitive evidence to allow for that. There must be prosecution and legal recourse against false accusations. We need to respect innocent until proven guilty.

If you lose a court case be it civil or criminal the loser should be required to shoulder the total financial burden of all legal proceedings and if that person during the course of the legal proceedings the plaintiff or defendant is found to have committed perjury or have born false witness and is guilty of deception they must be held accountable for their actions and must have criminal penalties brought against them.

We cannot allow for double standards in our legal system and must at the very least require evidence other than an accusers testimony as sufficient evidence of abuse.

column5:
As much as I would like someone to put a bullet in Hannity's head and think that Katie Hopkins is the worst person the UK has to offer, they're right about the fact that it's ridiculous that the women have taken this long to come out. Women need to grow a backbone when it comes to something like this. Not only are allegations this long after the fact extremely difficult, if not impossible, to prove but they're equally difficult, if not impossible, for the accused to disprove. And yet people go into a mob mentality over it.

Here in the UK allegations of this nature have now been made against MPs in parliament. Last week a member of the Welsh Assembly committed suicide after allegations were made against him and he was dismissed from his post in the Welsh Government without due process simply on the basis of, as yet, unproven allegations.

But, like Hopkins points out, dare to question allegations (and remember, that's ALL they are at this stage) and you're immediately accused of victim blaming, especially by women's groups and feminists. We had this exact issue in the UK within the past couple of years with the Ched Evans case (look it up). Every time someone criticised the witch-hunt against him, or the fact that he had a right to due process, the moronic mob would criticise causing the individual who made the comments to have to apologise for telling the truth. It was pathetic. In the end, Evans had his rape conviction overturned - I have no idea how the hell those 12 village idiots in the jury convicted him in the first place.

Roy Moore is an asshole and I strongly suspect that he did everything that has been said of him but I'm not going to be a part of the mob mentality over something that's yet to be proven.

actually keurig licenses the K-cups to coffee companies. Coffee companies basically pay keurig for the k-cups and keurig ships them labeled for what ever coffee they want to fill them with.  That's how keurig makes their money.  It's not off the machines but rather the k-cups themselves.  Yes it's true that you see the coffee manufactures logo on the k-cups, but they get there because the coffee company pays licensing to keurig to fill them with their coffee and brand it for them. In turn Keurig gets a small amount of money for each k-cup sold. It's super cheap to make the k-cup so it's easy to profit from it.  But they sell their machines at a loss that's why they try to make it harder to use 3rd party cups (though some people make them, but it's not keurig supported and if they found out during repairs it'd void your warranty).

The stunning hypocrisy to claim to represent morality and family values, then in the same breath refuse to distance oneself from a man who is as awful as Roy Moore. And not just for fondling a 14 year old girl. In my mind it is stunning that it took these revelations to condemn this terrible person, who has made a career out of spouting hate, trampling on the Right‚Äôs beloved Constitution, and flouting the rule of law. 

But the hypocrisy here is staggering. Can you imagine if a story came out about, for example, Bernie Sanders or Al Franken weeks before an election? Would these same conservatives be outraged at the timing, at some person bringing up accusations that were decades old at such an opportune moment? Where were all the conservatives crying in outrage at the timing of James Comey reopening the Clinton investigation weeks before the presidential election? And that proved to be completely baseless. Where is your outrage about the political timing on that issue? But more importantly, the timing can easily be explained. You may not have noticed this, but there have been a rash of incidents of women and men coming forward and making such allegations, mostly against liberal Hollywood stars (where is your outrage there?), and the climate has changed from one where powerful men can intimidate people into silence over decades to one where there is strength and safety in numbers, and people feel that they will finally be listened to. The more of these events that occur, the more likely others will be to come forward themselves. But conservatives only seem to complain when it is their darling politicians or heroes that are being accused. I sense hypocrisy from the party of family values and the rule of law. And where are all the conservatives questioning the witnesses in the Harvey Weinstein, Bill Cosby and Kevin Spacey cases? Some of these cases date back decades. Why aren‚Äôt conservatives outraged that it took so long for these witnesses to come forward?

I would guess that after years of silence for some of these women the possibility of this guy becoming a US Senator was the last straw. This, combined with the new climate of women finally feeling safe to come forward, more than explains the timing. Conservatives would see this if they weren't blinded by loyalty to their tribe. Being honest and fair requires that we put aside our loyalties when people have done bad things. I can't imagine for one second that any Conservative would defend a Democratic Senator who had fondled a 14 year old girl. I don't recall the wave of outrage on the liberal side when Anthony Weiner was sentenced to prison, nor have liberals come forward to defend any of their fellow liberal Hollywood elites who have been accused of such things. The hypocrisy seems to only emanate from one side. If you are an honest and upright person then you must equally condemn a person from your own party. That is actual virtue, rather than the pretend version that we too often see. 

The truth is that these people don‚Äôt care at all about family values, the Constitution, or the rule of law. They care about their side winning, at all costs, no matter who gets trampled along the way, and that is why their side should never be allowed to hold power, because they clearly have no principles at all.
